[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:

- The Americas region reported 50.5% of the global newly reported cases and 50.8% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period, maintaining its dominance as the most severely affected region, having reported more than 9.7 million cases. The USA reported 42.5% of cases (47 183), followed by Brazil 23.2% (25 800), Colombia 10.3% (11 470), Peru 6.0% (6667), Argentina 4.8% (5376), Mexico 4.4% (4853), and Chile 1.6% (1762).

- The European region reported 13.2% of the global newly reported cases and 15.1% of the newly confirmed deaths globally. Spain reported 29.5% (8532) of the regional newly confirmed cases, followed by Russia 17.8% (5159), France 10.9% (3152), Kazakhstan 4.0% (1158), Ukraine 3.7% (1061), Turkey 3.4% (995), the UK 3.2% (928), Germany 3.0% (879), Romania 2.8% (823), and Israel 2.5% (711). While the proportions have decreased, the absolute numbers in a number of countries have not. The re-entry of Spain and France with increased reporting compensating for the weekend without reports.

- The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 4.4% of the global newly reported cases and 9.8% of global newly reported fatalities. Iraq reported 28.2 % (2735) of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Iran 26.7% (2598), Saudi Arabia 12.9% (1258), Morocco 6.8% (659), Pakistan 4.4% (432), Kuwait 4.0% (388), Bahrain 3.1% (299), (Oman 0% (0)), and Palestinian Authority 2.5% (244). Oman did not report any cases in the past 72 hours. Cases are increasing in Iraq and Morocco. This region remains highly active, with multiple countries still in a surge mode.

- The African region reported 4.2% of the global newly reported cases and 1.8% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 58.0% (5377) of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by, Ethiopia 6.3% (583), Kenya 5.9% (544), Algeria 5.5% (507), Cameroon 5.0% (463), and Nigeria 3.1% (288). While South Africa is the dominant country in the region, it has halved its daily case count in the past few days.

- The Western Pacific region reported 2.3% of the global newly reported cases and 1.5% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 61.2% (3145) of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Japan 22.8% (1171), Australia 7.7% (395), Singapore 4.4% (226), China 2.2% (114), Viet Nam 0.60% (31), and South Korea 0.66% (34). Japan and Australia continue an increase in transmission.

- The South East Asia region reported 25.3% of the global newly reported cases and 21.0% of global deaths. India reported 93.5% (52 050) of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Indonesia 3.0% (1679), and Bangladesh 2.4% (1356). India continues to be the driving force of the dominance of this region.

Impression: The overall picture is basically the same. The ordering of the regions has the Americas having the highest disease load and newly confirmed cases on a daily basis followed by the South East Asia region, then Europe followed by the Eastern Mediterranean, followed by the Africa region and the Western Pacific region representing the lowest daily caseload of all the regions.

Figure 2. The epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 4 Aug 2020, at the source URL above is an excellent visual representation of the epidemic as described in the above text. - Mod.MPP]

